<https://viaf.org/46883804> obo:IAO_0000115 "An American historian of human sexuality who has focused on same-sex attraction and changes in the social organization of sexuality over time. His works focus on the idea, rooted in social constructionism, that the categories with which society describes and defines human sexuality are historically and culturally specific, along with the social organization of sexual activity, desire, relationships, and sexual identities."@en .

<https://viaf.org/52924112> obo:IAO_0000115 "An American transgender woman who was the first person to become widely known in the United States for having gender-affirming surgery. Jorgensen grew up in the Bronx, New York City. Shortly after graduating from high school in 1945, she was drafted into the U.S. Army during World War II. After her military service, she attended several schools and worked; it is during this time she learned about gender-affirming surgery. Jorgensen traveled to Europe, and in Copenhagen, Denmark, obtained special permission to undergo a series of operations beginning in 1952."@en .

<https://w3id.org/ocd> a owl:Ontology ;
    dc:creator "Areej Muhajab; Alia I. Abdelmoty; Athanasios Hassoulas"@en ;
    dc:date "2026"@en ;
    dc:description "A comprehensive ontology for Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD) developed at Cardiff University. The ontology defines 80 OCD-specific concepts with formal Description Logic definitions, integrates nine existing biomedical ontologies through five documented reuse strategies, and provides systematic lexical enrichment of both concepts and object properties using the OntoLex-Lemon model. Developed using a two-stage human-machine methodology combining expert clinical validation with large language model benchmarking."@en ;
    dc:publisher "Cardiff University, School of Computer Science and Informatics"@en ;
    dc:title "OCD Ontology"@en ;
    dcterms:license <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/> ;
    rdfs:comment "2022-01-01",
        "An Ontology for Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder",
        "This ontology provides a structured representation of concepts related to Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder, informed by clinical definitions and patient experiences.",
        "Published in: Muhajab, A., Abdelmoty, A.I., and Hassoulas, A. (2026). Development, Evaluation, and Enrichment of an OCD Ontology: A Two-Stage Human-Machine Methodology. Journal of Biomedical Semantics. Available on BioPortal: https://bioportal.bioontology.org/ontologies/OCD"@en ;
    rdfs:seeAlso <https://bioportal.bioontology.org/ontologies/OCD>,
        <https://github.com/Aliaia/ocd-ontology> ;
    owl:versionIRI <https://w3id.org/ocd/1.0> ;
    owl:versionInfo "1.0"@en .

<https://w3id.org/ocd#accompaniedBy> a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:comment "An object property where the domain is \"Obsession\" and the range is \"Compulsion.\" This property indicates that an obsession is accompanied by a compulsion." ;
    rdfs:domain <https://w3id.org/ocd#Obsession> ;
    rdfs:range <https://w3id.org/ocd#Compulsion> .

<https://w3id.org/ocd#hasComorbidity> a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:comment "hasComorbidity is an object property used to link instances of \"mental disorders.\" It represents the relationship between a specific mental disorder and the potential presence of other mental disorders occurring simultaneously in an individual." ;
    rdfs:domain <https://w3id.org/ocd#Obsessive_Compulsive_Disorder> ;
    rdfs:range <https://w3id.org/ocd#Obsessive_Compulsive_Related_Disorder> .

<https://w3id.org/ocd#hasControlLevel> a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:comment "The object property hasControlLevel indicates the degree of control an individual has over a behavior, activity, intrusive thought, or urge. It links the subject (behavior, activity, thought, or urge) to its corresponding control level assessment." ;
    rdfs:subPropertyOf <https://w3id.org/ocd#hasCriteria> .

<https://w3id.org/ocd#hasDistressLevel> a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:comment "The object property hasDistressLevel specifies the level of distress associated with a particular behavior, activity, intrusive thought, or urge. It connects the subject (behavior, activity, thought, or urge) to its corresponding distress level assessment." ;
    rdfs:subPropertyOf <https://w3id.org/ocd#hasCriteria> .

<https://w3id.org/ocd#hasInterferenceLevel> a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:comment "The object property hasInterferenceLevel identifies the extent to which a behavior, activity, intrusive thought, or urge interferes with an individual's daily functioning. It connects the subject (behavior, activity, thought, or urge) to its corresponding interference level assessment." ;
    rdfs:subPropertyOf <https://w3id.org/ocd#hasCriteria> .

<https://w3id.org/ocd#hasSymptom> a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:comment "The object property hasSymptom links an instance of obsessive-compulsive and related disorders to its associated symptoms. This property is used to specify the symptoms that characterize a particular disorder within this category." ;
    rdfs:domain <https://w3id.org/ocd#Obsessive_Compulsive_Disorder> ;
    rdfs:range <https://w3id.org/ocd#Symptoms> .

<https://w3id.org/ocd-combined-enriched> a owl:Ontology ;
    rdfs:label "OCD Ontology - Combined with Lexical Enrichment and External Mappings" ;
    dcterms:created "2025-07-29" ;
    dcterms:creator "Combined from multiple sources" ;
    dcterms:description "Generated by combining 458 base triples, 3020 lexical enrichment triples, and 9387 external mapping triples." ;
    rdfs:comment "This comprehensive OCD ontology combines: (1) Base hand-crafted OCD concepts from domain experts, (2) Rich lexical enrichment using OntoLex vocabulary providing synonyms and alternative forms, (3) External semantic mappings to WordNet, OBO ontologies, and other knowledge bases. The ontology maintains focus on core OCD concepts while providing extensive semantic annotations for natural language processing, semantic search, and knowledge integration applications." .

